            <h2 id="what-the-review-is" class="govuk-heading-m">What the service is</h2>
            <p>The service forms part of the Animal Health and Welfare Pathway. It will provide payments to livestock keepers to fund livestock visits by vets.</p>
            <p>You can get funding for a vet or team chosen by a vet, to visit your farm if you keep:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>beef cattle</li>
              <li>dairy cattle</li>
              <li>sheep</li>
              <li>pigs</li>
            </ul>
            <h2 id="welfare-review" class="govuk-heading-m govuk-!-margin-top-3">Livestock health and welfare review</h2>
            <p>There are two parts to the [scheme name]. The first part is the livestock health and welfare review.</p>
            <p>A review will help you:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>test for specific endemic diseases in beef cattle, dairy cattle and pigs</li>
              <li>test the effectiveness of medicines to treat worms in sheep</li>
              <li>increase livestock productivity</li>
              <li>improve animal welfare</li>
            </ul>
            <p>After the vet has completed a health and welfare review, you can choose to have an endemic disease follow-up, where the vet tests for key diseases on the same species as your review.</p>
            <h2 id="follow-up" class="govuk-heading-m">Endemic disease follow-up</h2>
            <p>The second part is the endemic disease follow up; this must follow a review.</p>
            <p>A follow-up will help you:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>understand levels of diseases and syndromes on farm through targeted testing</li>
              <li>reduce key disease levels and improve disease and health status through bespoke vet advice and a detailed biosecurity assessment</li>
              <li>increase livestock productivity </li>
              <li>improve animal welfare</li>
            </ul>
            <p>You can choose the vet that you want to do the review or endemic disease follow-up. The review and follow-up are not an inspection or audit.</p>
            <p>This is a multiannual agreement which will allow you:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>to have up to 3 reviews over the course of your agreement, for one livestock type, every 10 months</li>
              <li>to then have up to 3 follow-ups on the same herd or flock within 10 months of the review</li>
            </ul>
            <h2 id="what-to-expect-from-a-review" class="govuk-heading-m">Check you’re eligible to apply</h2>
            <p>To be eligible to make an agreement and claim funding you must have a minimum number of animals present when the vet visits your farm to do the review or endemic disease follow-up.</p>
            <p>You must have one of the following:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>11 or more beef cattle</li>
              <li>11 or more dairy cattle</li>
              <li>21 or more sheep</li>
              <li>51 or more pigs</li>
            </ul>
            <p>The animals can be any age.</p>
            <p>The livestock must be registered in England and you must be responsible for their welfare when the vet carries out the review or endemic disease follow-up visit. You can apply at any time of the year.  </p>
            <p>Your business must have:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>a single business identifier (SBI) linked to a county parish holding (CPH) number registered in England</li>
              <li>a CPH number</li>
            </ul>
            <p>You can only apply for a review or endemic disease follow-up on a CPH registered in England.</p>
            <p>The CPH number cannot be:</p>
            <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
              <li>an 8,000 number used for abattoirs, pet food manufacturers, racing pigeon establishments and showgrounds</li>
              <li>a 9,000 number used for poultry keepers</li>
            </ul>
            <p>If you have received a lump sum payment to leave or retire from farming, you can still apply for a funding if you meet the qualifying criteria.</p>
            <h2 id="check-youre-eligible-to-apply" class="govuk-heading-m">How much funding you could get</h2>
            <p>You’ll get funding for each livestock type, not for each animal.</p>
